THE new IrnBru <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Advertising" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Advertising" target="_blank">advert</a> features an embarrassing <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Train" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Train" target="_blank">train</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Toilet" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Toilet" target="_blank">toilet</a> incident and pays tribute to a legendary <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Billy_Connolly" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Billy_Connolly" target="_blank">Billy Connolly</a> jokeIt starts with the dreaded <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sliding_Doors" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sliding_Doors" target="_blank">sliding doors</a> opening to reveal a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Isle_of_Man" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Isle_of_Man" target="_blank">man</a> on the throne in full <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_View_%28U.S._TV_series%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_View_%28U.S._TV_series%29" target="_blank">view</a> of two glamorous woman and a female drinks attendantThe stunned bloke makes a dash for the button but trips up and ends up on all fours with his trousers round his anklesThe deadpan drinks attendant hands him a can of IrnBru with the words âBottoms up sonâThe stricken chap takes a drink and is transformed into a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Caricature" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Caricature" target="_blank">caricature</a> of former <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Celtic_F.C." title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Celtic_F.C." target="_blank">Celtic</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Celebrity" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Celebrity" target="_blank">star</a> Frank McAvennieWith newfound <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Confidence_trick" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Confidence_trick" target="_blank">confidence</a> he flashes a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Smile" title="http://